  Video by: Chelsea Lotz, Business Report TV
 

Eskom said it was trying to reduce the level of unplanned breakdowns to below 9,500 megawatts to minimise loadshedding and avoid having to implement rotational blackouts next week.
"Eskom will provide a prognosis for the long weekend later today," it added.
The power utility says it is working with police to investigate alleged sabotage at its Tutuka power station in Mpumalanga province which wiped 2,000  megawatt off the grid and prompted it to implement Stage 6 loadshedding on Monday, which entails suppressing up to 6,000 MW of demand to avoid a total collapse of the grid.

On Friday it was implementing Stage 2 loadshedding until 11 pm.
African News Agency